Here's a typical `MauiProgram.cs` setup:

```csharp
using Microsoft.Extensions.Logging;

namespace MyMauiApp;

public static class MauiProgram
{
    public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
    {
        var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
        builder
            .UseMauiApp<App>()
            .ConfigureFonts(fonts =>
            {
                fonts.AddFont("OpenSans-Regular.ttf", "OpenSansRegular");
            });

        // HttpClient — singleton so connections are reused (avoids socket exhaustion)
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<HttpClient>();

        // Data service — singleton because it wraps HttpClient and holds no per-user state
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<IDataService, DataService>();

        // ViewModels — transient so each navigation gets a fresh instance with clean state
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainViewModel>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailViewModel>();

        // Pages — transient so they pair 1:1 with their ViewModel instance
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainPage>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailPage>();

#if DEBUG
        builder.Logging.AddDebug();
#endif

        return builder.Build();
    }
}
```

**Why these lifetimes?**

| Registration | Lifetime | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `HttpClient` | **Singleton** | Reuses TCP connections; avoids socket exhaustion from repeated instantiation. |
| `IDataService` | **Singleton** | Stateless HTTP wrapper — one instance serves the whole app. Shares the single `HttpClient`. |
| `MainViewModel` / `DetailViewModel` | **Transient** | Each navigation should get fresh state (loaded data, form fields, etc.). Avoids stale data leaking between visits. |
| `MainPage` / `DetailPage` | **Transient** | Pages own their ViewModel. Matching lifetimes ensures a new page always gets a new ViewModel. |

**Key rule of thumb:** never register a transient service that depends on a scoped one, and never register a shorter-lived service that captures a longer-lived dependency in a way that would prevent disposal. Here, transient ViewModels depend on a singleton service — that's safe.

> **Note:** For production `HttpClient` usage, prefer `AddHttpClient<IDataService, DataService>()` from `Microsoft.Extensions.Http` — it manages handler rotation and avoids DNS caching issues that a raw singleton `HttpClient` can have.
